---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout>
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">
    <a 
      href="/"
      class="inline-flex items-center text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 mb-8 transition-colors"
    >
      <span class="mr-2">←</span> Back to Projects
    </a>
    
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-6 text-white">A Digital Garden of Ideas</h1>
    
    <div class="prose prose-lg prose-invert max-w-none">
      <p class="text-xl text-gray-300 mb-8">
        This is a space to cultivate ideas, tend to projects, and celebrate growth in all its forms.
      </p>
      
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-4 text-white">What is a Digital Garden?</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-300">
        A digital garden is a collection of notes, ideas, and projects that are continuously tended to, much like a real garden. Some ideas are just seeds, others are sprouting, and some have grown into mature plants.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-gray-300">
        This approach reframes projects not as a list of things to be "finished," but as living things that grow and evolve over time.
      </p>
      
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-4 text-white">Garden Plot Status</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-300">
        Each project, or "plot," in this garden has a status reflecting its current stage of growth:
      </p>
      
      <ul class="space-y-3 mt-4 text-gray-300">
        <li class="flex items-start">
          <span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded-full bg-green-500 mt-1.5 mr-3 flex-shrink-0"></span>
          <span><strong class="text-white">Sprouting</strong> - New ideas just beginning to grow.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start">
          <span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded-full bg-blue-500 mt-1.5 mr-3 flex-shrink-0"></span>
          <span><strong class="text-white">Fallow</strong> - A field left to rest and regain its nutrients for future growth.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start">
          <span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded-full bg-purple-500 mt-1.5 mr-3 flex-shrink-0"></span>
          <span><strong class="text-white">Composting</strong> - Older projects broken down to enrich new ones.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start">
          <span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded-full bg-yellow-500 mt-1.5 mr-3 flex-shrink-0"></span>
          <span><strong class="text-white">Dormant</strong> - A seed waiting for the right season to grow.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start">
          <span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded-full bg-indigo-500 mt-1.5 mr-3 flex-shrink-0"></span>
          <span><strong class="text-white">Needs More Sun</strong> - A good idea that needs better conditions to thrive.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start">
          <span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded-full bg-teal-500 mt-1.5 mr-3 flex-shrink-0"></span>
          <span><strong class="text-white">Evergreen</strong> - A sturdy plant that remains vibrant and useful year-round.</span>
        </li>
        <li class="flex items-start">
          <span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded-full bg-pink-500 mt-1.5 mr-3 flex-shrink-0"></span>
          <span><strong class="text-white">Mature</strong> - A fully-grown plant that has borne fruit.</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
      
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mt-10 mb-4 text-white">The Philosophy of the Garden</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-300">
        Gödel's Incompleteness Theorems taught us that no mathematical system can be both complete and consistent. 
        Similarly, I've found that creative pursuits often face a tension between completion and exploration.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-gray-300">
        This project embraces the idea that incompleteness isn't a flaw but a feature - a necessary 
        condition for growth, learning, and the kind of unexpected connections that define neurodivergent thinking.
      </p>
      
      <div class="italic text-gray-400 border-l-4 border-gray-700 pl-4 py-3 mt-10">
        "A project is never completed, only abandoned." — Paul Valéry (adapted)
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>